Support for React Native

Addons that depend on React need to work for either React or React
Native. To support both, addons have been refactored to export a
function that takes React as a parameter and returns the addon.

Addons should now be imported like so:

`import { FluxComponent } from 'flummox/addons/react`

or

`import { FluxComponent } from 'flummox/addons/react-native`

For convenience, addons for regular React can still be imported the old
way using `flummox/component`, `flummox/mixin`, etc.
Action args should be sent to each async action handler

Improved Store `register` methods

This cleans up Store's `register`, `registerAsync`, `registerAll`, and
`registerAllAsync` methods -- and the corresponding logic in
`Store#handler()` -- so that the code paths are simpler and easier to
follow. It also adds the ability for multiple handlers to be registered
for the same action.

This is also changes, in a breaking way, the args that are passed to
action handlers. Every action handler is now passed as the final
argument the entire payload from the dispatcher. This allows us to
provide extra information to the handlers; e.g. a dispatch id to
enable fine-grained optimistic updates (not implemented yet).

Async "begin" handlers no longer receive as arguments the same arguments
passed to the action -- they receive the dispatcher payload.

Refactor Store state changing methods

Rewrite store methods so they are agnostic to the type of state. Default
state type will still be an object.

- Remove undocumented method `getState()`.
- Add static method `mergeState()`. The default implementation is just
  `Object.assign()`, but by overriding this single method, you could add
support for any type of state, e.g. Immutable.js Records. Method
signature is `mergeState(oldState, newState)`. `oldState` may be undefined.
- `setState()`, `replaceState()`, and private method `_performHandler()`
  have been rewritten to use `mergeState()`.
- Default state is undefined instead of an empty object.

Return value to action caller

Previously, actions always returned undefined (or, in the case of async
actions, a promise that resolved to undefined). This was to enforce the
unidirectional data-flow model of Flux, and prevent users from using
actions as helper functions. This seemed to cause more trouble than its
worth, however, because there are legitimate reasons for a caller to use
the return value of an actions -- primarily, testing.

This PR reverses that decision. Now, the return value of an action
method is both sent through the dispatcher and returned to the caller.

Allow for nested FluxComponents

Sometimes, a store state getter needs to use a prop derived from the
state of another store. Previously, when using FluxComponent, this
required the creation of an extra composite component to receive the
props and pass them to another FluxComponent.

With this commit, props on a FluxComponent are automatically transferred
to children. This lets you nest FluxComponents, so that the inner state
getters have access to props retreived by outer state getters.

In Flummox, "action id" and "constant" are roughly synonymous. "Action
id" is preferred, to emphasize that constants map directly to actions,
but both terms should be supported. This commit ensures that all
existing methods containing `actionId` or `constant` should have an
alias (or be an alias of) the equivalent method name using the other
term. All future methods should follow the same convention. Again,
"action id" is the preferred term.
